I think a lot about how the Millennials were the last generation to build relationships with artists without being expected to view them critically.
We have grown up in an age of media abundance, with a collective awareness of pop culture that no longer exists.
We could dive into things without having to consider where they came from, as it was not so easy to determine that back then.
We did not question the pedestal we placed them on. These parasocial relationships were so important and influenced our lives.
Therefore, we have such a strong tendency towards nostalgia.
When "The Office" was still on air, my friends and I would order pizza every Thursday and watch the show together.
This was very different from today with streaming, where 12 episodes come out all at once, and everyone watches whenever they want and posts on social media with "spoiler warnings" or discusses them in closed groups.
Subconsciously, we yearn for this universal community that used to dominate everything.
That's why so many of us still watch series like "The Office" or movies like "Anchorman", in which so many one-liners appeared that would be memes today.
We had brought all these one-liners, and assumed that most people would already understand them.
Today, we can no longer assume that everyone knows something, even if it spreads massively virally.
There is too much, and there is no way to systematize it. Can we really escape this oversaturation?
We are trapped in a vicious cycle, constantly discovering new content, only to realize then that the artist is greedy or hypocritical.
Therefore, we need to hold on to our nostalgia and simultaneously accept that the people who created the works we liked could also make significant mistakes.
We approach parasocial relationships with greater caution.
We know that it is hard to become rich and powerful without stepping on someone's toes on the way there.
Since we have lost collective awareness regarding media, we have developed a class consciousness that fosters our critical thinking.
There are still those among us who elevate someone to a pedestal, only to be shocked when they fall.
We are in a phase of transition, and I am curious to see where it will all lead.
Inclusion and safety should be the norm.
